Server configuration:

This is a general guide to installing the software.  It is not difficult
and does not need any outside software to operate.  Here are the
requirements:

1)  Posix compliant O/S.  Linux, BSD, Minix should all work.  I developed
    it on a Raspberry Pi 3B+ which runs a version of Debian Linux.
2)  A user account where the software can be installed and run.  This can
    be any account but I never recommend running as root as simple errors
    can cause endless issues.
3)  The server will need enough ram to hold all the disk images in memory.
    I used a Raspberry Pi 3B+ and a Raspberry Pi 400 during development.
    This is way overkill for what is needed.
    
Configuration is very basic needing two lines changed in server/csd.c
file.  Those two lines are near the front and are:

#define PDP_SP		"/dev/tty/ttyUSB0"
#define PDP_BAUD	B9600

PDP_SP (PDP Serial Port) will need to be defined.  I used a USB serial 
port dongle.  If you use the hardware bits and a level converter in your
Pi the port is something like /dev/ttyS0.  You do not want the OS on the
server presenting a login on this device.  As for the USB devices, I
must confess that I found it by doing a ls of the /dev/tty* devices,
plugging in the dongle and then doing another and seeing what was added.
There is probably an entry in /var/log somewhere when a USB device is
added/deleted which would work as well.  The user that runs the server
will need access to this device.  In my case the ttyUSB0 device was in
group dialout.  I added the server account to the dialout group.  You
could also just change the ownership since the server is probably going
to be the only program that uses that device.

You need to change the baud rate to match what the PDP-8 console port is
configured for.  9600 is about as slow as I would consider usable.
These are the accepted baud rate values.

            B50
            B75
            B110
            B134
            B150
            B200
            B300
            B600
            B1200
            B1800
            B2400
            B4800
            B9600
            B19200
            B38400
            B57600
            B115200
            B230400

It is not guaranteed that your hardware can support all of them.

Change those two lines in csd.c to match your config and run make to build the
server.

When I run the server I

1) Login as the user.
2) cd consd/server
3) ./csd

Server will start and enter terminal mode.  You can then boot OS/8 by
toggleing in the csd help boot loader.


BDTIME constant

At some future time we may want to patch this in but at this time it is
a fiddly value to change so just leave it at the 7530 default.  This
should work unless you decide to run at a baud rate lower than 9600 baud.
What follows are the notes I started writing up on this topic.  Then I
tried to change it and realized that my version checking code sees the
change as an unknown installed handler.

The constant BDTIME generates is the speed of the serial port and
machine combination which means it needs to be run on the machine it
will be used on.  In my own testing I obtained:

Baud	CONST	Notes:
9600	7771	Estimate on 8/S
9600	7636	Estimate on 8/L
9600	7632	Estimate on 8/I and PDP-12
9600	7625	Estimate on Straight 8 and Linc8
9600	7565	Measured on 8/a (M8315 CPU)
9600	7530	Measured on 8/e with M8655 (matches estimate)

19200	7774	Estimate on 8/S
19200	7717	Estimate on 8/L
19200	7715	Estimate on 8/I and PDP-12
19200	7713	Estimate on Straight 8 and Linc8
19200	7673	Estimate on 8/a (M8315 CPU) Not supposed to work on M8316
19200	7654	Measured on 8/e with M8655 (matches estimate)

38400	7726	Estimate on 8/e
57600	7744	Estimate on 8/e
115200	7762	Estimate on 8/e
230400	7771	Estimate on 8/e

An uncooperative Straight 8 had me estimate those times.  My similar
estimate for the 8/e gave those numbers exactly so there is a good
chance they are correct.  The estimate is (1/(bdrate/10))/lptime.
This gives a loop count needed to wait at least one character time.
Convert this to the 12 bit two's complement for the ISZ to use.  You
don't need to round up because there is enough overhead in the call
to the handler and in the hander before the loop.  The lptime constants
for the different machines are:

8/e	6.2us
8/a	7.5us
8	9.75us
LINC-8	9.75us
8/i	10.25us
PDP-12	10.25us
8/l	10.65us
8/s	148us

Those values for lptime are best guesses and might not be correct for
your particular machine.  Especially if it was molested when it was in
service.  The times for the 8/e might be wrong depending on the jumper
on the M8330.

Optimally this could be measured during the boot loader and patched on
the fly.  I spent a couple of hours trying to make this fit and it will
require a complete overhaul of the boot loader because it is a few words
too long.

Alternatively, you can just leave this at the default of 7530  and
accept slightly slower performance.

You absolutely will want to change BDTIME for an 8/s or if you are trying
to run this on an FPGA implementation which has some crazy fast
instruction cycle time (hundreds of mhz kind of thing).  It might not
even be possible to make the loop counter long enough on a fast enough
8 implementation.


Short way to generate the BDTIME constant.

The constant BDTIME can be generated by the program BDTIME.PA if you
can find a way to run it on your machine.  Here is a short version
that can be hand toggled in.

0200 Load
3215 Dep
6046 Dep
6041 Dep
5202 Dep
6046 Dep
6041 Dep
5212 Dep
1215 Dep
7041 Dep
7402 Dep
2215 Dep
5205 Dep
7402 Dep
0200 Load
Clear/Cont or Start depending on the machine.

The answer is in the AC if it halts at addr 211.  The HLT at 214 should
never be reached.

